Here's the TikZ code that visualizes the Average Confidence Score (ACS) decay phenomenon described:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=3.14mm]{standalone}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    xlabel={Tasks Progression},
    ylabel={Average Confidence Score (ACS)},
    xmin=0.5, xmax=5.5,
    ymin=0.2, ymax=1.0,
    xtick={1,2,3,4,5},
    xticklabels={Task 1, Task 2, Task 3, Task 4, Task 5},
    ytick={0.3,0.4,0.5,0.6,0.7,0.8,0.9},
    grid=both,
    grid style={dashed, gray!30},
    axis lines=left,
    width=10cm,
    height=6cm,
    legend style={at={(0.97,0.3)}, anchor=east}
]

% ACS Decay Curve
\addplot[
    color=blue,
    mark=*,
    line width=1.5pt,
    smooth
] coordinates {
    (1,0.85)
    (2,0.75)
    (3,0.62)
    (4,0.48)
    (5,0.38)
};
\addlegendentry{ACS}

% Fixed Threshold Line
\addplot[
    color=red,
    dashed,
    line width=1pt
] coordinates {
    (1,0.7)
    (5,0.7)
};
\addlegendentry{Fixed Threshold}

% Annotations
\node[align=center, fill=white, rounded corners=2pt, draw=gray!50] 
    at (3.5,0.55) {\small Decaying ACS\\reduces usable\\unlabeled data};

\draw[->, thick, gray!70] (3.2,0.68) -- (2.8,0.75);
\draw[->, thick, gray!70] (3.8,0.62) -- (4.2,0.5);

\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code produces a professional-quality visualization that:
1. Shows a clear decaying trend in ACS across tasks
2. Includes a fixed threshold line (red dashed)
3. Uses intuitive markers and smooth curves
4. Contains explanatory annotations
5. Maintains proper axis labels and grid lines
6. Follows standard scientific visualization conventions

The resulting plot effectively communicates how the decaying ACS values (blue line with markers) progressively fall below the fixed confidence threshold (red dashed line), demonstrating the reduced utilization of unlabeled data in later tasks.

